Vasari's <i>Lives of the Artists</i> Chapter on Brunelleschi</li>
<li id="cite_note-6"><b><a href="#cite_ref-6" title="">^</a></b> "Messer Paolo dal Pozzo Toscanelli, having returned from his studies, invited Filippo with other friends to supper in a garden, and the discourse falling on mathematical subjects, Filippo formed a friendship with him and learned geometry from him."<br />
Vasarai's <i>Lives of the Artists</i>, Chapter on Brunelleschi</li>
<li id="cite_note-7"><b><a href="#cite_ref-7" title="">^</a></b> Plato's Republic, Book X, 602d. <a href="http://etext.library.adelaide.edu.au/mirror/classics.mit.edu/Plato/republic.11.x.html" class="external free" title="http://etext.library.adelaide.edu.au/mirror/classics.mit.edu/Plato/republic.11.x.html" rel="nofollow">http://etext.library.adelaide.edu.au/mirror/classics.mit.edu/Plato/republic.11.x.html</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-8"><b><a href="#cite_ref-8" title="">^</a></b> Mathographics by Robert Dixon New York: Dover, p. 82, 1991.</li>
<li id="cite_note-9"><b><a href="#cite_ref-9" title="">^</a></b> "...the paradox is purely conceptual: it assumes we view a perspective representation as a retinal simulation, when in fact we view it as a two dimensional painting. In other words, perspective constructions create visual symbols, not visual illusions. The key is that paintings lack the depth of field cues created by binocular vision; we are always aware a painting is flat rather than deep. And that is how our mind interprets it, adjusting our understanding of the painting to compensate for our position."<br />
<a href="http://www.handprint.com/HP/WCL/perspect1.html" class="external free" title="http://www.handprint.com/HP/WCL/perspect1.html" rel="nofollow">http://www.handprint.com/HP/WCL/perspect1.html</a> Retrieved on December 25, 2006</li>
</ol>
